Paul:

What I have seen written here or on the Shavian group -- I forget where 
-- is that an alphabet used for communication among lay people untrained 
in linguistics and phonetics does not require, nor is it particularly 
useful for it to have, the precision which the IPA was designed for.  
The average writer is trying to communicate to another person at a 
distance, not think about whether an English &quot;p&quot; is aspirated or not.

Thus, I can be perfectly consistent with the manner in which I use QS 
vowels in my writing, and someone from another speech community such as 
Australia or Ireland, may write the same words with the same QS vowels 
that I used and be perfectly consistent in their writing, but the 
corresponding vowels are not pronounced exactly the same by myself and 
the other two writers.  That does not render QS useless or a toy.  In 
fact, it renders it more useful because it has flexibility which the IPA 
cannot have and enables it to work for, essentially, all English speakers.

When I write the word &quot;an&quot; in QS, even though I may sometimes in some 
contexts pronounce a schwa for the vowel, I do not spell it with a 
schwa.  I write it with &quot;a-t&quot; because that is the way the word sounds 
when pronounced standing alone or when emphasized.  It does not make 
sense to me to attempt to accurately portray the word one way in one 
sentence and another way when surrounded by different words.  That would 
be true chaos.  Nor should we spell words to ape poor or slovenly 
pronunciation.  Spelling a word as it sounds when properly and clearly 
enunciated seems the best course to me.

Paige

Paul Tremblay wrote:
&gt;
&gt; John Cowan wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Paul Tremblay scripsit:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; But above all this topic really shows the need for a standard 
&gt; mapping of
&gt; &gt; &gt; QS letters to IPA symbols. I can see that different people pronounce
&gt; &gt; &gt; words differently, but if each QS letter does not mean a very specific
&gt; &gt; &gt; sound, which should map to IPA, then the alphabet becomes 
&gt; ambiguous and
&gt; &gt; &gt; somewhat meaningless.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Such a mapping is unattainable, because even uncontroversial English
&gt; &gt; consonants map to more than one IPA sound depending on dialect and 
&gt; on the
&gt; &gt; surrounding sounds. English &quot;p&quot; is an aspirated unvoiced labial stop,
&gt; &gt; except after &quot;s&quot; where it loses aspiration; English &quot;b&quot; is an 
&gt; unaspirated
&gt; &gt; labial stop, but it can be voiced or voiceless or varying freely between
&gt; &gt; the two.
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; But English speakers don&#39;t make the distinction between an aspirated and
&gt; unaspirated P, so it doesn&#39;t really matter if the P is aspirated or not.
&gt; If B is not voiced, it is a p, right?
&gt;
&gt; I think you are splitting hairs. You can certainly look up pronociations
&gt; in any dictionary. If sounds can&#39;t be mapped to IPA, then what do
&gt; dictionaries do?
&gt;
&gt; If we can&#39;t map QS to IPA, then it is completely meaningless. Certainly,
&gt; there is no one way to spell a word. If you are now saying that QS
&gt; cannot be mapped to a standard prononciation, then that means I can
&gt; spell a word any way I want.
&gt;
&gt; Let me be more specific. If I write &quot;an&quot; as &quot;Ado-Nun,&quot; then I need
&gt; readers to understand that they are to pronounce this word with two 
&gt; sounds:
&gt;
&gt; 1. a vowel that is in the middle of the mouth with the mouth mid open.
&gt; (The so-called schwa sound)
&gt;
&gt; 2. a n sound (not sure how this is pronounced!)
&gt;
&gt; If we are to say that we cannot map QS to IPA, what is to prevent a
&gt; reader from reading this text as:
&gt;
&gt; 1. the frontal vowel sound with the mouth open (ae).
&gt;
&gt; 2. the n sound.
&gt;
&gt; Is QS to mean anything or is it just a plaything?
&gt;
&gt; Sorry to sound exasperated, but there has to be some agreement so we can
&gt; have a guide, especiallly with the vowels. I have wasted needless hours
&gt; because the inadequate manual shows you how to pronounce words by giving
&gt; examples of words, which is very imprecise and a form of circular
&gt; reasoning. Using IPA as a guide would certainly help newcomers and would
&gt; probably greatly help clarify things amongst experienced users.
&gt;
&gt; Paul
&gt;
&gt;  


